The '''shore plover''' ({{langx|mi|'''tūturuatu'''}}, [[Moriori language|Moriori]]: '''{{lang|rrm|tchūriwat'}}''', '''''Thinornis novaeseelandiae'''''), also known as the '''shore dotterel''', is a small [[plover]] [[endemism|endemic]] to [[New Zealand]]. Once found all around the New Zealand coast, it is now restricted to a few offshore islands. It is one of the world's rarest shorebirds, with a population of roughly 250.

== Taxonomy ==
The shore plover was [[Species description|formally described]] in 1789 by the German naturalist [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]] in his revised and expanded edition of [[Carl Linnaeus]]'s ''[[Systema Naturae]]''. He placed it with the plovers in the [[genus]] ''[[Charadrius]]'' and coined the [[binomial nomenclature|binomial name]] ''Charadrius novaeseelandiae''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Gmelin | first=Johann Friedrich | author-link=Johann Friedrich Gmelin| year=1789 | title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae: secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis | edition=13th | volume=1, Part 2 | language=Latin | location=Lipsiae [Leipzig] | publisher=Georg. Emanuel. Beer | page=684 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2656177 }}</ref> Gmelin based his description on the "New Zealand plover" that had been described and illustrated in 1785 by the English ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in his ''A General Synopsis of Birds''. The species had been collected near [[Queen Charlotte Sound / Tōtaranui|Queen Charlotte Sound]].<ref>{{ cite book | last=Latham | first=John | author-link=John Latham (ornithologist) | year=1785 | title=A General Synopsis of Birds | volume=3, Part 1 | publisher=Printed for Leigh and Sotheby | location=London | page=206; Plate 83 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40078973 }}</ref> In the late 20th century the shore plover was moved from the original genus ''Charadrius'' to its own genus ''Thinornis'',<ref name="Shorebirds"/> along with the [[hooded plover]] later in the early 2000s.<ref name=h&m4>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Dickinson | editor1-first=E.C. | editor1-link= Edward C. Dickinson | editor2-last=Remsen | editor2-first=J.V. Jr. | editor2-link=James Van Remsen Jr. | year=2013 | title=The Howard & Moore Complete Checklist of the Birds of the World | volume=1: Non-passerines | edition=4th | location=Eastbourne, UK | publisher=Aves Press | isbn=978-0-9568611-0-8 | page=205 | url= https://archive.org/details/howardmoorecompl0001howa/page/n205/mode/1up | url-access=registration }}</ref> A [[molecular phylogenetic]] study published in 2015 found that ''Thinornis'' was [[sister group|sister]] to the genus ''Charadrius''.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Dos Remedios | first1=N. | last2=Lee | first2=P.L.M. | last3=Burke | first3=T. | last4=Székely | first4=T. | last5=Küpper | first5=C. | date=2015 | title=North or south? Phylogenetic and biogeographic origins of a globally distributed avian clade | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=89 | pages=151–159 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2015.04.010| pmid=25916188 | bibcode=2015MolPE..89..151D | url=https://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/90572/3/WRRO_90572.pdf }}</ref> This was confirmed by another study published in 2022.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Černý | first1=David | last2=Natale | first2=Rossy | date=2022 | title=Comprehensive taxon sampling and vetted fossils help clarify the time tree of shorebirds (Aves, Charadriiformes) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=177 | article-number=107620 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2022.107620 | pmid=36038056 | bibcode=2022MolPE.17707620C }}</ref> The species is [[monotypic]]: no [[subspecies]] are recognised.<ref>{{ cite web | author=AviList Core Team | date=2025 | title=AviList: The Global Avian Checklist, v2025 | doi=10.2173/avilist.v2025 | doi-access=free | url=http://www.avilist.org/checklist/v2025/ | access-date=7 November 2025 }}</ref>

The "Auckland Islands shore plover" ''Thinornis rossii'', supposedly from the [[Auckland Islands]], is now generally considered to be a juvenile shore plover with an incorrectly recorded location.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book| edition = 4th| publisher = Te Papa Press| isbn = 978-1-877385-59-9| last1 = Gill| first1 = Brian J.| last2 = Bell| first2 = B. D.| last3 = Chambers| first3 = G. K.| last4 = Medway| first4 = D. G.| last5 = Palma| first5 = R. L.| last6 = Scofield| first6 = R. P.| last7 = Tennyson| first7 = A. J. D.| last8 = Worthy| first8 = T. H.| title = Checklist of the Birds of New Zealand| location = Wellington, N.Z.| date = 2010}}</ref>

== Description ==
[[Image:NZ Shore Plover.jpg|thumb|right|Shore plover juvenile|alt=Image of Shore plover juvenile]]
The shore plover is about 20 cm long, brown above and white below, with a black (male) or brown (female) mask; the brown back feathers have narrow pale fringes, giving a scaly appearance at close range. There is a distinctive white strip circling its head below its brown skullcap. Its legs are bright orange-red, and the bill orange-red (brighter in males than females) with a sharply defined dark tip. The wings are brown with a narrow white wingbar along the full length, and the tail brown with white sides. Juveniles differ in lacking the full dark face mask, and having the brown back feathers with broader pale fringes, giving a more strongly scaly appearance above.<ref name="Shorebirds">{{cite book | last1=Hayman | first1=Peter | last2=Marchant | first2=John | last3=Prater | first3=Tony | title=Shorebirds | publisher=Croom Helm | publication-place=London | date=1986 | isbn=0-7099-2034-2 | page=}}</ref><ref name=NZBO>{{Cite encyclopedia |last=Dowding |first=J. E. |date=2022 |title=Shore plover / tuturuatu |url= https://www.nzbirdsonline.org.nz/species/shore-plover |editor-last=Miskelly |editor-first=C. M. |encyclopedia=New Zealand Birds Online|publisher=|access-date=2 October 2024}}</ref>

== Distribution ==
Although this species was historically found only on the New Zealand coast, [[subfossil]] shore plover bones have been recovered from roosts of the extinct [[laughing owl]] near rivers many kilometres inland.<ref name=":3">{{Cite book|title=The Lost World of the Moa|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|date=2002|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=978-0-253-34034-4|location=Bloomington IN|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.}}</ref> [[Second voyage of James Cook|Cook's second expedition]] collected them from opposite ends of the [[South Island]], in [[Fiordland]] and the [[Marlborough Sounds]]. There are 19th century reports of shore plovers from the South Island and several parts of the North Island, but by the 1870s they had vanished from the mainland, surviving only on the [[Chatham Islands]].<ref name=NZBO /> Introduced predators such as [[Cats in New Zealand|feral cats]] and [[brown rat]]s were the main culprits in their decline.<ref name=DOC_main>{{Cite web |title= Tūturuatu/Tchūriwat'/Shore plover |url= https://www.doc.govt.nz/nature/native-animals/birds/birds-a-z/shore-plover/ |date= |website=Department of Conservation Te Papa Atawhai|publisher=|access-date=2 September 2024}}</ref> In 2026 the Shore Plover Recovery Group confirmed that a chick had fledged on [[Pitt Island]], the first time this has occurred in 150 years.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-03-08 |title=First shore plover fledgling born on Pitt Island in 150 years |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/national/588948/first-shore-plover-fledgling-born-on-pitt-island-in-150-years |access-date=2026-03-07 |website=RNZ |language=en-nz}}</ref>

== Breeding ==
[[File:Thinornis novaeseelandiae (AM LB1296) (cropped).jpg|alt=Image of egg of Thinornis novaeseelandiae|thumb|Egg, Auckland Museum collection]]
Shore plovers (unusually for shorebirds) nest under cover (such as driftwood and vegetation) or in burrows under boulders. This is likely to be for protection against avian predators; in their current range, [[skua]]s and [[gull]]s, while past predators would have included the laughing owl and the [[New Zealand falcon]].<ref name=":3" /> This is one of the reasons for their decline, as such nests are more vulnerable to mammalian predators.

In the early 1990s, the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] (DOC) started a captive breeding programme at [[Pukaha / Mount Bruce National Wildlife Centre]], and later at [[Isaac Conservation and Wildlife Trust]].<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2012/critically-endangered-nz-shore-plover-released-on-motutapu-island/ |title=Critically endangered NZ shore plover released on Motutapu Island |date=20 February 2012|website= |publisher=Department of Conservation Te Papa Atawhai|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref> From a captive population of around 6–10 pairs, over 500 captive-bred juveniles have been released into the wild.<ref name=NZBO />

== Conservation ==
Shore plovers are [[endangered species|endangered]], with a global population of around 250 birds.<ref name=DOC_main /> The species survived on only one island, [[South East Island/Rangatira|Rangatira]], in the [[Chatham Islands]], from where it has since been reintroduced to other offshore islands, such as [[Mangere Island]] in the Chathams, [[Mana Island (New Zealand)|Mana Island]] near Wellington and [[Motutapu Island|Motutapu]] near Auckland.<ref name=DOC_main /> The world population was roughly 70 breeding pairs in 1937 and their habitat was declared a reserve in 1954. The population fluctuated in the 1980s, with only 40 breeding pairs in 1982, rising to 80 pairs in 1987 and a high of 94 pairs in 2010.<ref name=NZBO /><ref name="coomber">{{cite book |title=Birds of the World |last=Coomber|first=Richard |publisher=Colour Library Books |year=1991 |isbn= 0-86283-806-1 |location=Godalming, Surrey |pages=[https://archive.org/details/photographicency0000coom/page/97 97–100] |chapter=Charadriiformes: Plovers |chapter-url= https://archive.org/details/photographicency0000coom/page/97 }}</ref> A second wild population of about 20 birds was discovered in 1999 living on Western Reef off [[Chatham Island]], but it gradually declined, and the last bird was taken into captivity in 2003.<ref name=":2" /> As of 2016, the wild population comprised 66 breeding pairs, 56 of them in the Chatham Islands.<ref name=DOC_main /> DOC has a stated goal of increasing the population to 250 in five different habitats.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |url =http://www.radionz.co.nz/national/programmes/afternoons/audio/201798877/critter-of-the-week-nicola-toki |title=Critter of the Week – Nicola Toki |last=Toki|first=Nicola|author-link=Nicola Toki|date=29 April 2016|website=RNZ|publisher=Radio New Zealand|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref>

DOC moved a number of captive-reared juveniles to Mana Island, off Wellington's western coast, between March and May 2007. They bred within months of their arrival, and in February 2008 twenty more were translocated. From a high of 87 individuals, the population was reduced to just 10 from the effects of a single [[brown rat]].<ref name=":4" />

Birds had also been translocated since 2000 to [[Portland Island (New Zealand)|Waikawa]] (Portland Island), a privately owned island off the [[Māhia Peninsula]] in Hawke's Bay. In 2012, the population on Waikawa was discovered to have crashed by 75% to just 20 birds,<ref name=Waikawa_tragedy/> apparently due to predation by a brown rat.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://faunarecovery.org.nz/2015/07/27/the-waikawa-shore-plover-saga/ |title=The Waikawa shore plover saga |first=Barry |last=Dent |date=27 July 2015 |publisher=Fauna Recovery New Zealand |access-date=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://blog.doc.govt.nz/2018/07/27/the-final-translocation-for-mahias-shore-plover/ |title=The final translocation for Mahia's shore plover? |date=27 July 2018 |work=Conservation Blog |publisher=Department of Conservation |access-date=6 December 2018}}</ref> Twelve eggs were rescued for translocation to Mana Island.<ref name=Waikawa_tragedy>{{Cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2013/tragedy-strikes-endangered-new-zealand-shore-plover-population/|title=Tragedy strikes endangered New Zealand shore plover population |date=4 February 2013|website= |publisher=Department of Conservation Te Papa Atawhai |access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref>

A total of 42 captive-bred shore plovers were released onto Motutapu Island in 2012 in the hope they would become established there and on other pest-free islands in the Hauraki Gulf.<ref name=":5" /> The birds repeatedly flew away, and only five were still present in 2015 when nineteen more were released.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.newshub.co.nz/nznews/shore-plovers-released-on-motutapu-island-2015012718 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160531102910/http://www.newshub.co.nz/nznews/shore-plovers-released-on-motutapu-island-2015012718 |archive-date= May 31, 2016 |title=Shore plovers released on Motutapu Island |last=Akel|first=Torben |date=27 January 2015|website=Newshub|publisher=Mediaworks TV|access-date=14 October 2023}}</ref> Motutapu had its mammalian predators removed in 2010, and the breeding population there increased from one pair in 2015 to three pairs in 2016.<ref name=":4" /> These birds are currently the most accessible to the public.

Six juveniles were released into the wild in 2018.<ref name="BirdGuides">{{cite web |title=Critically Endangered plover enjoys record breeding season |url=https://www.birdguides.com/news/critically-endangered-plover-enjoys-record-breeding-season/ |publisher=[[BirdGuides]] |access-date=9 February 2019 |language=en |date=9 February 2019}}</ref> Four additional juveniles were released in February 2019 with a further 21 due to be released on 25 March, having been bred at the [[Pukaha / Mount Bruce National Wildlife Centre|Pūkaha National Wildlife Centre]].<ref name="BirdGuides" />  Five more juvenile birds were transported from a captive breeding program in Christchurch to Mana Island in April 2020.<ref name="roy-2020">
